0:["U-lORNS7aBHvRAQjr-f8q",[[["",{"children":["address-finder",{"children":["__PAGE__",{}]}]},"$undefined","$undefined",true],["",{"children":["address-finder",{"children":["__PAGE__",{},[["$L1",[["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"WebApplication\",\"name\":\"Address Finder\",\"url\":\"https://getmylocations.com/address-finder\",\"applicationCategory\":\"UtilitiesApplication\",\"operatingSystem\":\"Web\",\"isAccessibleForFree\":true,\"offers\":{\"@type\":\"Offer\",\"price\":\"0\",\"priceCurrency\":\"USD\"}}"}}],["$","main",null,{"className":"max-w-5xl mx-auto px-5 py-10","children":[["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-8","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-electric-400 font-semibold mb-2","children":"Free Tool · Two-way Geocoding"}],["$","h1",null,{"className":"font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold tracking-tight leading-[1.05]","children":["Address ",["$","span",null,{"className":"text-electric-400","children":"Finder"}]," — address ↔ GPS coordinates"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-lg text-slate-300/90 mt-4 max-w-3xl","children":"Type any address, landmark, or place name and get the GPS coordinates. Or paste a latitude/longitude pair and get the nearest street address back. Powered by OpenStreetMap Nominatim."}]]}],["$","$L2",null,{}],["$","section",null,{"className":"mt-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"What this tool does"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"The page does two related jobs. Type in an address or a landmark name — “Eiffel Tower”, “1600 Pennsylvania Ave”, “Badshahi Mosque, Lahore” — and it returns the latitude and longitude. Paste a coordinate the other way and it tells you the nearest street address. Both lookups call OpenStreetMap’s Nominatim service, which is free for low-volume use and covers most of the world."}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"mt-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"Why house numbers are sometimes one or two off"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"Map databases rarely have a coordinate stored for every individual house number. Instead, they store the start and end of each street, the range of numbers along it (say 1 to 199 on the north side), and they slide along the line to estimate where number 47 sits. This works fine on a tidy block. It falls apart when houses are spaced unevenly, when one giant property took up four old plots, or when a street was renumbered decades ago and the records still reflect the old pattern."}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"The result is the familiar pattern of a pin that lands two houses short, or on the wrong side of a small street. For everyday use this is close enough; for couriers, it is the reason packages occasionally end up next door."}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"mt-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"Where geocoding works well, and where it does not"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"Coverage is uneven. North America, western Europe, Japan, South Korea, and Australia have near-complete address data. Major cities in Pakistan, India, the Middle East, and Africa are usually well covered for streets but inconsistent for individual buildings. Rural areas anywhere in the world tend to fall back to whichever village or district the coordinate is in."}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"When a lookup fails, adding context usually fixes it. “Main Street” on its own resolves to nothing useful. “Main Street, Springfield, Illinois” works fine. The same logic applies to landmarks — adding the city and country disambiguates the dozens of “Central Park”s out there."}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"mt-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"Rate limits and fair use"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"The free Nominatim endpoint asks users to keep traffic to about one request per second per IP. That is fine for a manual page like this one. If you need to geocode thousands of addresses at once, either self-host Nominatim — the data is free to download — or use a paid commercial geocoder. Hammering the free endpoint will get your IP temporarily blocked."}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"mt-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"If you found this useful"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"grid sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4 gap-3 mt-5","children":[["$","$L3","/my-location",{"href":"/my-location","className":"glass rounded-2xl p-4 hover:ring-electric-400/40 ring-1 ring-white/10 transition no-underline","children":["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-display text-base font-bold text-slate-100 hover:text-electric-400 transition","children":"My Location"}]}],["$","$L3","/gps-coordinates",{"href":"/gps-coordinates","className":"glass rounded-2xl p-4 hover:ring-electric-400/40 ring-1 ring-white/10 transition no-underline","children":["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-display text-base font-bold text-slate-100 hover:text-electric-400 transition","children":"GPS Coordinates"}]}],["$","$L3","/coordinates-converter",{"href":"/coordinates-converter","className":"glass rounded-2xl p-4 hover:ring-electric-400/40 ring-1 ring-white/10 transition no-underline","children":["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-display text-base font-bold text-slate-100 hover:text-electric-400 transition","children":"Coordinates Converter"}]}],["$","$L3","/reverse-geocoding",{"href":"/reverse-geocoding","className":"glass rounded-2xl p-4 hover:ring-